MALARIA, FALCIPARUM - JAMAICA: (ST. CATHERINE) REQUEST FOR INFORMATION
*****************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

Date: Sat 14 Mar 2009
Source: The Jamaica Star [edited]
<http://www.jamaica-star.com/thestar/20090314/news/news2.html>


Five persons associated in some way with Caymanas Park, located in
the communities of Independence City and Gregory Park, have been
infected with malaria since January [2009].

As a result, the Ministry of Health, through their Kingston/St Andrew
and St Catherine health departments, carried out a malaria
eradication and education drive at Caymanas Park on Saturday [14 Mar
2009] dubbed 'The Malaria Derby.'

The health ministry used the opportunity to educate the masses,
mostly men, on the dangers of the disease and requested voluntary
blood testing for traces of the disease. More than 130 persons were tested.

Strict measures
---------------
The ministry has not prevented races from being held at the track,
but stipulated strict measures for the organisers of the horse racing
industry to adhere to. A major one is that races should finish before
dusk, which is when mosquitoes are most dangerous. "We want them (the
organisers) to close off before dusk, we don't want anyone to be
bitten," said Dr Eva Lewis-Fuller, director of the Healthy Lifestyle
Programme in the Ministry of Health told The Portmore Star.

The ministry has taken nothing for granted and the entire premises
was fogged a day prior to Saturday's raceday. "We did some fogging
last night (last Friday) [13 Mar 2009] to rid the premises of
mosquitoes," she continued.

Malaria is a disease, which is contracted via the bite of a female
anopheles mosquito. The mosquito passes a parasite into the blood
stream of the unsuspecting victim.

Signs and symptoms
------------------
Signs and symptoms of malaria include fever, sweating, chills,
headaches, weakness, and vomiting. If you experience these symptoms,
you should contact your doctor or the nearest health centre.

